issue.title: `sst bind` fails on stacks containing a Service with bound constructs
issue.body:
_Discord discussion: https://discord.com/channels/983865673656705025/1166372275185000598_

---

## Description:

When running the `sst bind` command on a stack that contains a `Service` with constructs bound through the `service.bind` call, a TypeError is thrown: `Cannot read properties of null (reading 'addEnvironment')`. This error seems to occur because `this.container` is `null` when running locally.

## Steps to reproduce:

1. Create a stack with a `Service`.
1. Bind constructs to the `Service` using the `service.bind` call (do not set it in the constructor).
1. Run the `sst bind` command on the stack.

## Expected result:

The `sst bind` command should successfully bind the constructs to the Service.

## Actual result:

The `sst bind` command throws a `TypeError: Cannot read properties of null (reading 'addEnvironment')`.

## Additional information:

The error does not occur if the binds are defined in the Service itself. It only happens if `service.bind` is called separately. The error also appears when running `sst remove`.

A potential workaround was suggested, which involves checking if `this.doNotDeploy` is true before calling this.container.addEnvironment(name, value) and attachPermissionsToRole(this.taskDefinition.taskRole, permissions). However, this workaround causes `sst bind` to hang indefinitely without printing anything.


```js
 addEnvironmentForService(name, value) {
    if (!this.doNotDeploy){
        this.container.addEnvironment(name, value);
    }
}
attachPermissionsForService(permissions) {
    if (!this.doNotDeploy){
        attachPermissionsToRole(this.taskDefinition.taskRole, permissions);
    }
}
```

The issue could be related to the `app.mode` being set as remove during `sst bind`. Further investigation is required to determine the root cause and find a proper solution.

issue.title: Astro static generation doesn't fail build
issue.body:
The default output mode for Astro sites is `static` (SSG), which isn't supported by the `astro-sst` adapter. The current implementation allows a successful build but fails at the deployment stage when the SSR function is not found (because it doesn't exist).

Either, the `astro-sst` adapter should detect the `outputMode: static` and immediately fail with a warning, or the `AstroSite` construct should be able to pivot when static content is detected to utilize the `StaticSite` construct.

pull_request.title: feat: add astro static support
pull_request.body:
Add astro-sst/static adapter
Add static deployment with CF request function

Resolve #3442

----
This implementation solves the issue of Astro's default output mode being `static` and the `astro-sst` package failing late in the deployment phase for `static` outputs.

Rather than using a `StaticSite` construct, this still leverages the `AstroSite` construct built on the `SsrSite` construct so projects can switch from `static` to `ssr` or `hybrid` without completely redeploying (though changing the package from `astro-sst/static` to `astro-sst/lambda` will be required). This also means that the work to handle routing and redirects at the CloudFront Function level can be used with static outputs to provide a much more developer experience with clean URLs and dynamic header based redirects.

The adapters also now throw early errors if the output mode does not match the supported mode of the adapter.

----
### Static Mode Configuration (`astro.config.mjs`):
```js
import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config'
import aws from 'astro-sst/static'

export default defineConfig({
  site,
  adapter: aws()
})
```

### Server Mode Configuration (`astro.config.mjs`):
```js
import { defineConfig } from 'astro/config'
import aws from 'astro-sst/lambda'

export default defineConfig({
  site,
  output: 'hybrid',
  adapter: aws()
})
```

issue.title: fix: support warming requests in remix server
issue.body:
Open to suggestions on a better way to do this, but
https://github.com/sst/sst/blob/master/packages/sst/support/remix-site-function/regional-server.js#L84
throws an error when it receives a request from a warming function (event.headers is undefined)

comment.body:
Thanks @michaelgmcd.

The warmer function expects a predefined return response format — https://github.com/michaelgmcd/sst/blob/98db2fae5a7c84cf0875f62c5188bfb05a58a362/packages/sst/support/ssr-warmer/index.ts#L69

Also added a `setTimeout` to ensure the warming requests takes some time to respond, so a lambda instance don't end up handling multiple warming requests.

Can you give it a try and see if it works?
